The DhQ key is random each time it is run, saved to file Rxg.  He encrypts it with:

gpg --batch --yes -r "RansomKey" -o qgffrqdGlfhrdoE -e RxgXlDqP0h3baha

Checked the params here, -r is for 'recipient'.  -o is output to file. -e is encrypt data:

-r, --recipient USER-ID     encrypt for USER-ID
-o, --output FILE           write output to FILE
-e, --encrypt               encrypt data

Found some other stuff to try:

[https://github.com/kudelskisecurity/volatility-gpg](https://github.com/kudelskisecurity/volatility-gpg)

This repository contains Volatility3 plugins that can retrieve partial and full gpg passphrases from gpg-agent's cache.

gpg_partial.py may retrieve at most 8 characters from a passphrase for gnupg using versions of libgcrypt [older than 1.8.9](https://dev.gnupg.org/T5597).

[https://research.kudelskisecurity.com/2022/06/16/gpg-memory-forensics/](https://research.kudelskisecurity.com/2022/06/16/gpg-memory-forensics/)

GPG MEMORY FORENSICS

[June 16, 2022](https://research.kudelskisecurity.com/2022/06/16/gpg-memory-forensics/) [Sylvain Pelissier](https://research.kudelskisecurity.com/author/sylvainpelissier/) [cryptography](https://research.kudelskisecurity.com/tag/cryptography/) [Leave a comment](https://research.kudelskisecurity.com/2022/06/16/gpg-memory-forensics/#respond)

Pretty Good Privacy (PGP) and the open source implementation GNU Privacy Guard (GPG) are encryption solutions following the [OpenPGP standard](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc4880.txt).

Cutting right to the chase here.. Excerpt:

[Volatility](https://github.com/volatilityfoundation/volatility3/releases/tag/v1.0.1) is a widely used forensics framework. It is used to analyze volatile memory dump artifacts to extract data. For example, it has been used in the past to recover [Bitlocker volume encryption](https://github.com/elceef/bitlocker) keys while they are in RAM or to solve [challenges](https://bienaime.info/media/sstic2020_bienaime.pdf) of previous SSTIC editions. The framework is highly customizable and allows writing plugins in Python to fit specific needs. Therefore, we developed [two plugins](https://github.com/kudelskisecurity/volatility-gpg) for Volatility3. The first plugin retrieves partial (or complete, up to 8 characters) passphrases from memory by searching in gpg-agent‘s memory the constant IV of aes-wrap. This plugin would not work on versions of GPG later than version 2.3.4.
